WEBVTT

00:01.392 --> 00:02.915
- Previously,
on "God Friended Me"...

00:02.959 --> 00:04.134
- You know Falken's
real name?

00:04.178 --> 00:06.441
- What was it?
- Henry Chase.

00:06.484 --> 00:08.051
- One of these students
must have written the article

00:08.095 --> 00:09.966
about Henry Chase.
Her name's Pria Amar.

00:10.010 --> 00:11.576
She hasn't seen Henry
since college.

00:11.620 --> 00:15.189
- Lucky for you, I've kept
the article I wrote.

00:15.232 --> 00:17.060
- After reading the articles,
I started inputting

00:17.104 --> 00:18.975
all the coordinates
of all the Friend Suggestions

00:19.019 --> 00:21.630
associated with them.
- A Fibonacci Spiral.

00:21.673 --> 00:25.242
- Our next friend suggestion
is gonna complete the Spiral

00:25.286 --> 00:27.114
and pinpoint the location.

00:27.157 --> 00:29.594
- For what?
- Falken.

00:31.074 --> 00:33.685
- Ladies and gentlemen,
please welcome back

00:33.729 --> 00:35.470
to the "Millennial Prophet"
my old friend

00:35.513 --> 00:37.559
and OG podcast guest,

00:37.602 --> 00:39.604
Rabbi Zoe Schwartz.

00:39.648 --> 00:41.519
- Thank you, Miles.
It's good to be back.

00:41.563 --> 00:43.565
We certainly have a lot
to chat about.

00:43.608 --> 00:45.654
- Well, I can tell that
you are dying to talk about

00:45.697 --> 00:48.309
the God Account, so let's talk.

00:48.352 --> 00:50.876
- Miles, I'm not here to judge.
I've known you since college.

00:50.920 --> 00:52.835
All you've ever wanted to do
is help people.

00:52.878 --> 00:55.185
It sounds like whoever's
behind this God Account

00:55.229 --> 00:57.448
is giving you that chance,
and you've embraced it.

00:57.492 --> 00:58.971
- Thank you, Zoe.
- Yeah.

00:59.015 --> 01:00.625
- I--I have to admit,
the God Account--

01:00.669 --> 01:03.324
with all of its mystery--
has given me a sense

01:03.367 --> 01:05.717
of purpose, and it feels good.

01:05.761 --> 01:07.110
- I'm happy for you, Miles,

01:07.154 --> 01:09.721
but as a rabbi,
I would be remiss not to say

01:09.765 --> 01:12.463
that what you're doing--
reaching out to strangers,

01:12.507 --> 01:14.117
changing lives--
is an act of God.

01:14.161 --> 01:16.032
- You sound just like
my father.

01:16.076 --> 01:18.208
- Ooh, speaking
of Reverend Finer,

01:18.252 --> 01:20.036
how are things between you
and Vader?

01:20.080 --> 01:22.647
- [laughs]
Actually, pretty great.

01:22.691 --> 01:24.780
- So I guess
the only thing left

01:24.823 --> 01:27.130
is just figuring out
who's behind the God Account

01:27.174 --> 01:28.871
and why they chose you.

01:28.914 --> 01:30.873
- Well, you came
at a great time, Zoe,

01:30.916 --> 01:32.440
because I am about
to drop some news

01:32.483 --> 01:34.094
for all of my listeners.

01:34.137 --> 01:36.748
My friends and I have unmasked

01:36.792 --> 01:38.750
the man behind
the digital curtain,

01:38.794 --> 01:42.363
found a hidden pattern
that will lead to Oz himself.

01:42.406 --> 01:44.234
- Sounds like you have it
all figured out, Miles,

01:44.278 --> 01:46.454
but just remember:

01:46.497 --> 01:48.586
every great story in the Torah,

01:48.630 --> 01:50.545
there's always a test
in the end.

01:50.588 --> 01:53.548
Are you prepared for that?

01:53.591 --> 01:55.854
- Well, I guess we're about
to find out.

01:55.898 --> 01:57.769
[cheerful music]

01:57.813 --> 02:00.772
- So have you told Miles
you broke up with Eli?

02:00.816 --> 02:02.470
- It just happened, Parker.

02:02.513 --> 02:04.385
- Like, three days ago.

02:04.428 --> 02:06.169
That's like a month
in the dating world.

02:06.213 --> 02:07.344
- [laughs]
Okay.

02:07.388 --> 02:08.867
I'm gonna tell him, okay?

02:08.911 --> 02:11.261
And before you ask,
breaking up with Eli

02:11.305 --> 02:13.524
had absolutely nothing
to do with Miles.

02:13.568 --> 02:16.179
- Of course.

02:16.223 --> 02:19.530
- Besides, he's with Nia,
so it...

02:19.574 --> 02:21.184
doesn't matter.

02:21.228 --> 02:23.578
- Cara, I wanted
to let you know

02:23.621 --> 02:25.884
I have made a decision
about the opening in features.

02:25.928 --> 02:27.756
Congratulations,
you got the job.

02:27.799 --> 02:29.279
- That's amazing, thank you.

02:29.323 --> 02:30.802
- Finish up whatever article
you're working on.

02:30.846 --> 02:32.978
You start Monday.

02:33.022 --> 02:34.458
- Congrats!

02:34.502 --> 02:36.199
I know how badly
you wanted this.

02:36.243 --> 02:38.027
- Yeah.
[laughs]

02:38.070 --> 02:40.116
- So now that you're moving on
from local stories,

02:40.160 --> 02:42.640
I guess this means
no more God Account.

02:42.684 --> 02:44.381
♪

02:44.425 --> 02:46.427
- Yeah.

02:46.470 --> 02:48.690
Yeah, I guess it does.

02:48.733 --> 02:50.735
♪

02:50.779 --> 02:52.041
[knocking on door]

02:52.084 --> 02:54.826
- Ali.
- Morning, Dad.

02:54.870 --> 02:57.742
Where should I put them?
- Uh, on the table is fine.

02:57.786 --> 02:58.874
- Okay.

02:58.917 --> 03:00.441
- They're beautiful.

03:00.484 --> 03:03.139
- Mom's favorite.
- Mm-hmm.

03:03.183 --> 03:06.186
- Can't believe it will be
17 years tomorrow.

03:08.275 --> 03:10.059
- Your mother wanted peonies

03:10.102 --> 03:13.062
for her wedding bouquet...

03:13.105 --> 03:15.499
but there was a, um--

03:15.543 --> 03:19.068
uh, well, a mix-up
with the florist on the day,

03:19.111 --> 03:22.767
and she got a bouquet
full of calla lilies instead.

03:22.811 --> 03:25.248
Oh, God, she was so upset.
- Hmm.

03:25.292 --> 03:28.425
- At first, the day was ruined,

03:28.469 --> 03:31.950
but by the end of the wedding,
she, uh, insisted

03:31.994 --> 03:34.126
that calla lilies were
her new favorite flower.

03:34.170 --> 03:35.780
- [laughs]

03:35.824 --> 03:37.347
Oh, I gotta run.
I gotta open up the bar.

03:37.391 --> 03:40.307
- Oh, oh, um, I was thinking:

03:40.350 --> 03:43.353
since things are going well
with your brother and I,

03:43.397 --> 03:46.574
maybe he'd like
to join us this year

03:46.617 --> 03:48.619
at the cemetery.

03:48.663 --> 03:51.143
- [soft laugh]
I can ask.

03:51.187 --> 03:52.797
- Oh, that'd be great.
Thank you.

03:52.841 --> 03:54.669
- Bye, Dad.

03:54.712 --> 03:57.672
[hopeful music]

03:57.715 --> 04:02.329
♪

04:02.372 --> 04:05.027
- So I narrowed down
the possible center

04:05.070 --> 04:07.029
of the Fibonacci Spiral
to a radius

04:07.072 --> 04:08.857
of about ten square blocks,

04:08.900 --> 04:11.207
and I was studying the Spiral
when I suddenly remembered

04:11.251 --> 04:13.427
something from Pria's article
on Henry Chase.

04:13.470 --> 04:16.038
She mentioned
this electronics store

04:16.081 --> 04:17.735
where he bought
his first computer,

04:17.779 --> 04:19.824
the computer that changed
the trajectory of his life,

04:19.868 --> 04:21.478
and that address
just so happens

04:21.522 --> 04:24.438
to be inside
this ten-block radius.

04:24.481 --> 04:25.830
This is where
you guys are like,

04:25.874 --> 04:28.050
"Rakesh, you are a genius.

04:28.093 --> 04:30.705
Thank you, Rakesh."
[cell phone chimes]

04:30.748 --> 04:34.404
Well, here we, uh...

04:34.448 --> 04:36.798
here we are.

04:36.841 --> 04:38.365
- Huh.

04:38.408 --> 04:40.584
You sure you still want
to go with "genius"?

04:40.628 --> 04:42.325
[lighthearted music]

04:42.369 --> 04:43.805
- Well, it looks like
they just opened.

04:43.848 --> 04:46.286
Google Maps
must not have updated it.

04:46.329 --> 04:48.897
I was just so sure
that this would lead us

04:48.940 --> 04:50.246
to Falken, you know?

04:50.290 --> 04:53.118
- Well, it was
a valiant effort, Rakesh.

04:53.162 --> 04:55.295
- Guess we'll just have to wait
for another Friend Suggestion

04:55.338 --> 04:57.514
to narrow it down.

04:57.558 --> 05:04.391
♪

05:04.434 --> 05:06.610
- Hey, uh, you hear anything

05:06.654 --> 05:09.091
about your big promotion?

05:09.134 --> 05:10.788
- Uh, yeah.

05:10.832 --> 05:12.616
Yeah, actually, I--

05:12.660 --> 05:15.010
where's Miles?
- Um...

05:15.053 --> 05:16.794
- Hey.

05:16.838 --> 05:19.362
♪

05:19.406 --> 05:21.233
- Miles?

05:21.277 --> 05:24.324
♪

05:24.367 --> 05:25.977
- Miles.

05:26.021 --> 05:27.109
Hey.

05:27.152 --> 05:29.894
Hey, what's up?

05:29.938 --> 05:32.157
- This is the intersection
where my mom was killed

05:32.201 --> 05:35.552
in the car accident.

05:35.596 --> 05:37.859
Tomorrow it'll be 17 years.

05:37.902 --> 05:39.426
[somber music]

05:39.469 --> 05:42.820
- Miles, I'm so sorry.

05:42.864 --> 05:45.214
- You know, this...

05:45.257 --> 05:48.304
intersection is
within the ten-block radius

05:48.348 --> 05:50.480
of the Fibonacci Spiral.
[cell phone buzzes]

05:50.524 --> 05:52.569
Can't be a coincidence.

05:52.613 --> 05:56.617
♪

05:56.660 --> 05:58.575
- It's not.

05:58.619 --> 06:00.577
♪

06:00.621 --> 06:02.753
- Who's "Charles Cole"?

06:02.797 --> 06:05.147
- He's the drunk driver
that killed my mom.

06:05.190 --> 06:07.105
♪

06:07.149 --> 06:08.803
I mean, why would
the God Account

06:08.846 --> 06:10.587
send me his name?
Why would it ever think

06:10.631 --> 06:12.023
that I would want to help him?

06:12.067 --> 06:15.070
- You know how
the God Account works.

06:15.113 --> 06:16.985
He obviously was sent to you
for a reason.

06:17.028 --> 06:18.595
- I don't care!

06:18.639 --> 06:20.336
There is no way in hell
I'm gonna help the guy

06:20.380 --> 06:22.425
that killed my mom!

06:22.469 --> 06:24.253
- Miles.

06:24.296 --> 06:26.734
Miles, if we don't help him,
we can't complete the Spiral.

06:26.777 --> 06:29.650
- Then we find another way.

06:29.693 --> 06:32.304
- Okay, look, maybe we should
just give you a second.

06:32.348 --> 06:33.567
Take a break.

06:33.610 --> 06:35.743
- I'm fine, okay?

06:35.786 --> 06:38.006
Charles Cole is off-limits.

06:38.049 --> 06:41.313
We're not helping him.
Understood?

06:41.357 --> 06:43.490
both: Okay.

06:43.533 --> 06:46.493
[tense music]

06:46.536 --> 06:49.844
♪

06:58.026 --> 07:00.811
- You okay?

07:00.855 --> 07:02.726
- I don't know.

07:02.770 --> 07:05.250
I mean, there is a line
I never thought

07:05.294 --> 07:07.383
the God Account would cross,

07:07.427 --> 07:10.038
but sending me Charles Cole?

07:10.081 --> 07:11.474
They crossed it.

07:11.518 --> 07:13.084
- Yeah.

07:13.128 --> 07:14.477
[mellow music playing
over speakers]

07:14.521 --> 07:16.261
But still...

07:16.305 --> 07:18.829
this can't be a coincidence.

07:18.873 --> 07:22.311
- You think I should
help this guy.

07:22.354 --> 07:24.748
- I think that this might be

07:24.792 --> 07:27.490
about more than helping
Charles Cole.

07:27.534 --> 07:28.970
- I'm fine.

07:29.013 --> 07:30.972
I don't need any help.

07:31.015 --> 07:32.974
- Okay.

07:33.017 --> 07:35.933
♪

07:35.977 --> 07:39.110
Me and Dad are gonna go down
to the cemetery tomorrow.

07:39.154 --> 07:40.851
You haven't been
in a long time.

07:40.895 --> 07:43.680
Maybe you can join us.
- That's you and Dad's thing.

07:43.724 --> 07:45.247
- So let's make it
an "us" thing.

07:45.290 --> 07:47.162
I mean, you guys are finally
in a good place,

07:47.205 --> 07:49.904
and I know it would mean
a lot to him...

07:49.947 --> 07:52.167
and I think it would be
good for you.

07:52.210 --> 07:54.299
- Thanks...

07:54.343 --> 07:56.345
but I'm okay.

07:56.388 --> 07:59.479
♪

07:59.522 --> 08:02.525
- So what do Cara

08:02.569 --> 08:05.528
and Rakesh think
about you refusing to help?

08:05.572 --> 08:09.053
- They're my friends,
and they respect my decision.

08:09.097 --> 08:11.186
- I don't know, Cara.

08:11.229 --> 08:12.622
Miles told us
to leave this alone.

08:12.666 --> 08:14.711
I think we should respect
his decision.

08:14.755 --> 08:17.888
- Look, when Miles got
that Friend Suggestion,

08:17.932 --> 08:20.935
I have never seen him
so angry.

08:22.153 --> 08:24.025
I mean, I think maybe
this might be about him

08:24.068 --> 08:27.681
finally confronting his past.

08:27.724 --> 08:29.944
- Okay, um--so you said

08:29.987 --> 08:32.294
you followed Charles Cole
to a fire station.

08:32.337 --> 08:33.730
You--you know why he's there?

08:33.774 --> 08:35.645
- No, but I gotta go.

08:35.689 --> 08:37.168
He just walked out.

08:37.212 --> 08:39.562
I'm gonna go find out
what he was doing.

08:39.606 --> 08:41.564
[inquisitive music]

08:41.608 --> 08:43.435
- After the gear's checked,
I want everyone out back

08:43.479 --> 08:46.264
for drills.

08:46.308 --> 08:47.265
- Excuse me.

08:47.309 --> 08:49.746
Hey, I--I'm Cara Bloom.

08:49.790 --> 08:51.574
- Captain Daniel Estes.

08:51.618 --> 08:53.184
How can I help you?

08:53.228 --> 08:55.883
- Um, I'm a journalist
for an online magazine,

08:55.926 --> 08:58.625
and I'm writing a story
on Charles Cole.

08:58.668 --> 09:01.105
I just saw him leave here,
and I was hoping you might

09:01.149 --> 09:03.543
be able to tell me
why he stopped by?

09:03.586 --> 09:05.327
- I'm sorry, but I can't
help you with that.

09:05.370 --> 09:08.069
If you'll excuse me...

09:08.112 --> 09:09.853
- Wait, please.

09:09.897 --> 09:11.986
- Look, last thing
Charlie needs is a reporter

09:12.029 --> 09:13.640
digging up his past.

09:13.683 --> 09:17.513
- Yeah, that's--that's not
actually why I'm here.

09:17.557 --> 09:18.732
Truth?

09:18.775 --> 09:20.124
I'm not here for a story.

09:20.168 --> 09:22.605
I'm here because of my friend.

09:22.649 --> 09:24.694
His mother was in the car
Charles crashed into

09:24.738 --> 09:26.740
that night.

09:26.783 --> 09:29.394
- I'm sorry.
- I was thinking if...

09:29.438 --> 09:32.659
maybe he could talk to Charles,
it might help somehow.

09:32.702 --> 09:35.270
I just wanted to get
a little background first.

09:35.313 --> 09:38.142
- Charles and I went
through the Academy together.

09:38.186 --> 09:40.188
We kept in touch
over the years,

09:40.231 --> 09:41.755
not as much
as I would have liked.

09:41.798 --> 09:44.366
- He wanted to be a fireman?
- Yeah.

09:44.409 --> 09:46.890
That's actually why
he stopped by.

09:46.934 --> 09:49.850
He wants to reapply
to the Academy.

09:49.893 --> 09:52.766
He was hoping I could
give him a recommendation.

09:52.809 --> 09:55.159
- And you're not gonna
give him one?

09:55.203 --> 09:57.684
- Even if I did, I doubt
it would make a difference,

09:57.727 --> 10:00.817
not with his criminal record--
which is a shame.

10:00.861 --> 10:04.342
Charles was only 18 when
he went through the Academy.

10:04.386 --> 10:06.649
From day one he knew he wanted
to be the best,

10:06.693 --> 10:09.260
and he was.

10:09.304 --> 10:10.784
The night we graduated,
we all went out

10:10.827 --> 10:13.221
to Crowley's Bar to celebrate.

10:14.918 --> 10:16.311
When I woke up
the next morning,

10:16.354 --> 10:18.705
I found out about the accident.

10:18.748 --> 10:20.402
[somber music]

10:20.445 --> 10:24.188
- Well, thank you
for speaking with me.

10:24.232 --> 10:26.495
Oh, um...

10:26.538 --> 10:28.758
you know,
after all these years,

10:28.802 --> 10:31.892
do you know why he's reapplying
to the Academy now?

10:31.935 --> 10:34.416
- Age limit for enrollment
is 36.

10:34.459 --> 10:37.114
Charles' birthday
is next month.

10:37.158 --> 10:40.683
Guess he figured he'd give it
one last shot.

10:40.727 --> 10:42.816
- Thanks.

10:42.859 --> 10:48.256
♪

10:48.299 --> 10:50.040
[computer chirps]

10:50.084 --> 10:52.303
- It's no use, Miles.

10:52.347 --> 10:54.131
I've tried everything
I can think of

10:54.175 --> 10:57.439
in order to figure out how
to complete the Spiral, but...

10:57.482 --> 10:58.875
there's no way around it.

10:58.919 --> 11:00.703
I need at least a few more
data points,

11:00.747 --> 11:03.053
and the only way to get them...

11:03.097 --> 11:04.533
is through
our Friend Suggestion.

11:04.576 --> 11:06.578
- Rakesh--
- I'm not trying to push.

11:06.622 --> 11:08.711
- You're not?
- Okay, okay, I am.

11:08.755 --> 11:11.758
I am, but just because
helping him might be

11:11.801 --> 11:13.368
the only way
we're gonna find Falken.

11:13.411 --> 11:15.500
[knocking on door]

11:19.156 --> 11:20.723
- Hey.
- Hey, what's up?

11:20.767 --> 11:22.986
- Uh, so I know you said
Charles Cole was off-limits,

11:23.030 --> 11:24.901
but I think I know
why the God Account

11:24.945 --> 11:26.207
sent you his name.

11:26.250 --> 11:29.210
- I've already told you,
I don't care.

11:29.253 --> 11:31.603
- Okay, well, this isn't
just about you.

11:31.647 --> 11:33.518
I mean, we're all
in this together.

11:33.562 --> 11:35.477
We've all been helping
these Friend Suggestions.

11:35.520 --> 11:38.045
You can't just expect Rakesh
and I to walk away.

11:39.568 --> 11:41.309
- Just for the record,
I told her to respect

11:41.352 --> 11:43.137
your decision,
but please go ahead.

11:43.180 --> 11:45.313
- Look, Miles, the night
of the accident,

11:45.356 --> 11:47.619
Charles had just graduated
from the Fire Academy,

11:47.663 --> 11:49.273
top of his class.

11:49.317 --> 11:51.275
He was gonna be a firefighter
and he still wants to be.

11:51.319 --> 11:52.755
- Well, no one's stopping him.

11:52.799 --> 11:54.714
- Yeah, but no one's
helping him, either.

11:54.757 --> 11:56.367
- Good.

11:56.411 --> 11:58.152
He does not deserve my help.

11:58.195 --> 11:59.762
- Well, how do you know that?

11:59.806 --> 12:01.938
Okay, you don't know
anything else about him.

12:01.982 --> 12:03.853
- I don't need to know
anything else about him.

12:03.897 --> 12:05.594
That's the point.

12:05.637 --> 12:06.987
- No--no, the point is that
you don't want to know

12:07.030 --> 12:08.815
anything else about him,
because if you did,

12:08.858 --> 12:10.730
if you knew who he was
before that night

12:10.773 --> 12:13.471
or who he's been since then,
he'd become a real person,

12:13.515 --> 12:15.430
and not just some ghost
that you can be angry at

12:15.473 --> 12:17.562
and never have to face.

12:17.606 --> 12:19.260
♪

12:19.303 --> 12:21.131
- She's right, Miles.

12:21.175 --> 12:23.177
I've known you
for a long time, man,

12:23.220 --> 12:24.874
and I think you owe it
to yourself

12:24.918 --> 12:27.050
to talk to this man.

12:27.094 --> 12:32.142
♪

12:32.186 --> 12:34.405
- Can I interrupt?
- Ah, always.

12:34.449 --> 12:37.365
Twice in one day.
Here, what's on your mind?

12:38.192 --> 12:40.324
- [sighs]

12:41.673 --> 12:45.025
The God Account sent Miles
a new Friend Suggestion.

12:45.068 --> 12:46.678
- Mm?

12:46.722 --> 12:48.724
- Charles Cole.

12:48.768 --> 12:51.727
[tense music]

12:51.771 --> 12:57.037
♪

12:57.080 --> 12:59.561
- I imagine that did not
go down well.

12:59.604 --> 13:01.258
- No, it didn't.

13:01.302 --> 13:03.478
He refuses to help him.

13:03.521 --> 13:05.741
I think he should, but he's
not ready to hear that yet.

13:05.785 --> 13:08.352
- I'm afraid he might never be.

13:08.396 --> 13:10.354
- Maybe.

13:10.398 --> 13:12.748
♪

13:12.792 --> 13:15.925
Which is why...

13:15.969 --> 13:18.972
I think you need
to finally tell him.

13:19.015 --> 13:22.105
He may not be ready to hear it,
but he needs to, Dad.

13:22.149 --> 13:26.153
♪

13:26.196 --> 13:28.155
- I know, I know.

13:28.198 --> 13:30.897
It's just...

13:30.940 --> 13:34.378
it's taken us so long
to get back to where we are,

13:34.422 --> 13:36.859
to the kind of relationship
I've always wanted for us.

13:36.903 --> 13:39.819
- That's why it's important
that it comes from you.

13:39.862 --> 13:44.606
♪

13:44.649 --> 13:47.261
- I'll talk to him,
just not today.

13:47.304 --> 13:49.350
We both know how
that conversation will go.

13:49.393 --> 13:51.874
I just need to get through
the next few days

13:51.918 --> 13:55.704
and remember your mother
in peace, if that's okay.

13:55.747 --> 13:57.488
- Of course.

13:57.532 --> 14:01.101
♪

14:01.144 --> 14:03.233
- I'm glad you decided
to do this.

14:03.277 --> 14:05.932
- No matter what he says,
I'm not helping him.

14:05.975 --> 14:07.934
- I'm not asking you to,
all right?

14:07.977 --> 14:10.458
I'm just asking you
to talk to him.

14:13.026 --> 14:14.462
Hey.

14:14.505 --> 14:17.421
It's been 17 years
for him as well.

14:17.465 --> 14:18.988
My guess is you're not
the only one

14:19.032 --> 14:21.164
who's thought about this.

14:21.208 --> 14:23.166
- And if he hasn't?

14:23.210 --> 14:25.908
- Well, then, we leave.

14:25.952 --> 14:28.476
We never come back.

14:28.519 --> 14:31.348
[suspenseful music]

14:31.392 --> 14:33.350
- Yeah.

14:33.394 --> 14:35.918
♪

14:35.962 --> 14:38.442
[door alarm ringing]

14:38.486 --> 14:45.406
♪

14:45.449 --> 14:47.625
- Can I help you?

14:47.669 --> 14:51.107
♪

14:51.151 --> 14:53.675
- My name is Miles Finer.

14:53.718 --> 14:56.721
I think it's time
we finally talk.

14:56.765 --> 14:58.898
♪

15:06.906 --> 15:08.690
- I always knew
this day would come, but...

15:08.733 --> 15:12.172
[sighs]
Now that it's here, I, uh--

15:12.215 --> 15:15.001
I don't really know
where to begin.

15:16.654 --> 15:18.482
- Miles.

15:23.444 --> 15:26.577
- Tomorrow will be 17 years...
[sighs]

15:26.621 --> 15:29.319
Since you took my mother
from me.

15:30.320 --> 15:32.670
Do you know that?

15:32.714 --> 15:35.804
Does that day
mean anything to you?

15:35.847 --> 15:38.589
- [sighs]
Of course it does.

15:41.070 --> 15:42.289
I don't think
about what happened

15:42.332 --> 15:43.420
just one day a year.

15:43.464 --> 15:46.684
I think about it every day.

15:46.728 --> 15:50.166
- You know she had
just beat cancer.

15:51.167 --> 15:54.736
She had her whole life
ahead of her, and you stole it.

15:58.653 --> 16:02.004
- You know, nothing I can say
will ever make things right,

16:03.571 --> 16:05.747
but clearly...

16:05.790 --> 16:07.836
you came here looking
for answers, so anything

16:07.879 --> 16:11.013
that you want to ask,
please go ahead.

16:15.278 --> 16:18.107
- Why did you get in that car
that night?

16:18.151 --> 16:21.284
[somber music]

16:21.328 --> 16:23.591
- I've asked myself

16:23.634 --> 16:26.637
that same question
for 17 years,

16:26.681 --> 16:29.727
and the answer is always
the same...

16:29.771 --> 16:31.860
[sighs]

16:31.903 --> 16:34.297
I don't know.

16:34.341 --> 16:36.517
I'd just graduated
the Fire Academy.

16:36.560 --> 16:38.388
Everyone was going out
to celebrate.

16:38.432 --> 16:41.565
I thought I was totally fine
to drive home...

16:41.609 --> 16:45.352
[sighs]
And obviously I wasn't.

16:45.395 --> 16:46.918
I mean, I was a kid.

16:46.962 --> 16:50.052
I was 18 years old--
and that's not an excuse.

16:50.096 --> 16:53.186
No, it's...

16:53.229 --> 16:55.710
you know, it was just
a mistake.

16:55.753 --> 16:58.321
♪

16:58.365 --> 17:00.584
Things...

17:00.628 --> 17:04.066
weren't supposed
to turn out like this.

17:04.762 --> 17:08.070
- That's why you're reapplying
to the Academy.

17:08.114 --> 17:10.551
Hoping for a second chance.

17:10.594 --> 17:12.901
♪

17:12.944 --> 17:14.816
- Yeah, ever since I was
a little kid, I always wanted

17:14.859 --> 17:16.905
to be a firefighter.

17:16.948 --> 17:19.647
♪

17:19.690 --> 17:22.650
But instead of saving lives...

17:22.693 --> 17:23.825
♪

17:23.868 --> 17:26.262
I ended up taking one.

17:26.306 --> 17:31.920
♪

17:31.963 --> 17:33.965
I'm sorry, Miles.

17:34.009 --> 17:35.576
♪

17:35.619 --> 17:38.318
I'm truly sorry.
[sniffles]

17:38.361 --> 17:43.323
♪

17:43.366 --> 17:45.281
[door opens]

17:45.325 --> 17:47.109
- Sweetie?
I'm home.

17:47.153 --> 17:50.504
Got out of work early,
figured I'd surprise you.

17:50.547 --> 17:52.027
Oh.
- [sniffs]

17:52.071 --> 17:53.811
- Hi.
[laughs]

17:53.855 --> 17:55.509
I didn't know you had company.

17:55.552 --> 17:57.511
Hi, I'm Angela.

17:57.554 --> 17:59.643
I'm Charles' fiancée.

17:59.687 --> 18:02.168
So weird, I'm still not used
to saying that.

18:02.211 --> 18:04.257
[laughs]
- I'm Cara.

18:04.300 --> 18:06.302
- Miles.
- Hey.

18:06.346 --> 18:10.132
So, how do you guys
know Charles?

18:10.176 --> 18:12.613
- They're just old friends.

18:12.656 --> 18:15.920
Listen, do you mind--
- Whoa, um, I'm sorry.

18:19.794 --> 18:21.361
She doesn't know, does she?

18:21.404 --> 18:24.190
- Know what?
- Um...

18:24.233 --> 18:27.280
♪

18:27.323 --> 18:29.586
- Unbelievable.
- Miles, please.

18:29.630 --> 18:32.372
- No, we're not friends.

18:32.415 --> 18:35.157
We're anything but.

18:35.201 --> 18:37.507
- I--I don't understand.

18:37.551 --> 18:39.988
So how do you know each other?

18:40.031 --> 18:41.729
♪

18:41.772 --> 18:44.427
- He killed my mom.

18:44.471 --> 18:46.560
♪

18:46.603 --> 18:47.735
- Charles?

18:47.778 --> 18:51.130
What is he talking about?

18:51.173 --> 18:52.914
- I can explain, okay?

18:52.957 --> 18:54.263
Um...

18:54.307 --> 18:56.787
it was a long time ago.

18:56.831 --> 18:59.312
I had too much to drink,
I got behind the wheel

18:59.355 --> 19:01.575
of a car--
- Oh, my God.

19:01.618 --> 19:04.795
♪

19:04.839 --> 19:07.276
- Did you go to jail?

19:07.320 --> 19:09.060
- Yes.

19:09.104 --> 19:11.585
- Were you ever gonna tell me?

19:11.628 --> 19:15.110
♪

19:15.154 --> 19:17.895
I'm glad I found out now.

19:17.939 --> 19:21.247
♪

19:21.290 --> 19:22.857
[door closes]

19:22.900 --> 19:24.424
- [sighs]

19:24.467 --> 19:26.556
- Miles.

19:26.600 --> 19:29.907
Miles, slow down.

19:29.951 --> 19:31.344
Miles, talk to me.

19:31.387 --> 19:32.780
- Look, I'm not apologizing,
okay?

19:32.823 --> 19:34.303
He doesn't get
to ignore the past

19:34.347 --> 19:35.913
as if it never happened.

19:35.957 --> 19:37.567
- I'm not saying he does,
and I'm not defending him,

19:37.611 --> 19:40.266
but he didn't strike me
as the kind of guy

19:40.309 --> 19:41.702
who wants to ignore the past.

19:41.745 --> 19:43.399
- Then why did he lie
to his fiancé?

19:43.443 --> 19:45.227
- I don't know, okay?

19:45.271 --> 19:47.577
But walking away now
is not gonna fix anything.

19:47.621 --> 19:50.232
- You think I care about
making his life better?

19:50.276 --> 19:52.800
He does not deserve
a second chance.

19:52.843 --> 19:55.106
- I'm not talking
about him, Miles.

19:55.150 --> 19:57.239
I was talking about you.

19:57.283 --> 19:59.110
[melancholy music]

19:59.154 --> 20:01.678
Look, I know how hard
this must be...

20:01.722 --> 20:03.071
♪

20:03.114 --> 20:04.942
But this isn't you, Miles.

20:04.986 --> 20:07.684
You see the good in people

20:07.728 --> 20:10.121
even when others can't.

20:10.165 --> 20:12.602
♪

20:12.646 --> 20:14.387
If you don't face this now,
you are gonna be

20:14.430 --> 20:15.953
running forever.

20:15.997 --> 20:18.173
- You wanted me
to come down here.

20:18.217 --> 20:20.001
I came.

20:20.044 --> 20:22.308
I'm done.

20:22.351 --> 20:28.749
♪

20:28.792 --> 20:31.752
[choir vocalizing]

20:31.795 --> 20:34.015
♪

20:34.058 --> 20:37.061
- ♪ Make your way

20:37.105 --> 20:39.020
♪ To the river

20:39.063 --> 20:42.415
♪ Amen

20:42.458 --> 20:45.635
♪ Make your way

20:45.679 --> 20:47.811
♪ To the river

20:47.855 --> 20:51.598
♪ Amen

20:51.641 --> 20:55.732
♪ He is down
by the river ♪

20:55.776 --> 21:00.694
♪ Make your way
to the river ♪

21:00.737 --> 21:05.438
♪ Bring your faith
to the river ♪

21:05.481 --> 21:09.137
♪ Amen

21:09.180 --> 21:14.011
♪ He is healing
at the river ♪

21:14.055 --> 21:18.494
♪ Bring your pain
to the river ♪

21:18.538 --> 21:19.887
♪ Bring your pain

21:19.930 --> 21:21.541
[knocking on door]

21:21.584 --> 21:23.673
♪ Bring your pain

21:23.717 --> 21:25.153
Hey, what's up?
- Hey.

21:25.196 --> 21:27.068
Uh, sorry to just drop by.

21:27.111 --> 21:29.026
I know what today means to you.

21:29.070 --> 21:31.028
You got a second?
- Yeah, is everything okay?

21:31.072 --> 21:33.335
- Uh, I don't know.
I don't know.

21:33.379 --> 21:35.337
I kept digging into
Charles Cole,

21:35.381 --> 21:37.470
hoping I could find
something in his life

21:37.513 --> 21:39.385
that would help me complete
the Fibonacci Spiral--

21:39.428 --> 21:40.908
- I'm guessing by the tone
of your voice

21:40.951 --> 21:42.431
and your inability
to keep still

21:42.475 --> 21:44.172
you found something.

21:44.215 --> 21:47.697
- I did, um, but it's not
what I was expecting.

21:47.741 --> 21:50.091
So we know Charles
is reapplying

21:50.134 --> 21:52.702
for the Fire Academy, um,
but it's not his first time.

21:52.746 --> 21:55.401
- So?
- So, about seven years ago

21:55.444 --> 21:57.664
he applied, and since he had
a felony, he had to go

21:57.707 --> 22:00.014
before a board and--
I mean, ultimately

22:00.057 --> 22:01.929
he didn't get in, but...

22:01.972 --> 22:06.237
he got pretty close
thanks to a, uh, recommendation

22:06.281 --> 22:08.109
from a prominent member
of the community.

22:08.152 --> 22:09.980
- Who?

22:10.024 --> 22:12.026
- Your dad.

22:12.069 --> 22:15.029
[mellow music]

22:15.072 --> 22:17.292
♪

22:17.336 --> 22:19.381
- We need to talk.

22:19.425 --> 22:20.774
- Miles, what's wrong?

22:20.817 --> 22:23.385
- I know what you did
for Charles Cole.

22:23.429 --> 22:25.082
♪

22:25.126 --> 22:26.693
- Miles--
- No, no!

22:26.736 --> 22:30.174
How can you help the man
that killed your wife?

22:30.218 --> 22:33.482
♪

22:33.526 --> 22:36.703
- About a year
after your mother died,

22:36.746 --> 22:38.966
I went to see him in prison.

22:39.009 --> 22:41.751
I need to look into his eyes

22:41.795 --> 22:44.275
and have him do the same,
and what I saw

22:44.319 --> 22:46.800
was a man full of regret,
full of sorrow,

22:46.843 --> 22:49.716
a man who made a mistake
and paid for it,

22:49.759 --> 22:52.675
and when he was released,
he wanted to volunteer

22:52.719 --> 22:54.155
his services to give back,

22:54.198 --> 22:56.418
and so I supported him,
because it was

22:56.462 --> 22:58.377
the right thing to do.

22:58.420 --> 23:01.728
- If it was the right thing
to do, why lie to me about it?

23:01.771 --> 23:05.253
- Because you weren't ready
to hear the truth.

23:05.296 --> 23:07.777
You were so angry,
and whether you know it or not,

23:07.821 --> 23:08.822
you still are.

23:08.865 --> 23:10.737
- Yeah,
yeah, I still am,

23:10.780 --> 23:13.870
but the real question is,
why aren't you?

23:13.914 --> 23:18.484
♪

23:18.527 --> 23:21.748
- When your mother
first got sick...

23:21.791 --> 23:24.707
we had to prepare for the worst
as we were praying

23:24.751 --> 23:28.494
for the best, which meant
having conversations...

23:28.537 --> 23:30.191
about the end.

23:30.234 --> 23:32.585
What we would say to you

23:32.628 --> 23:34.500
and your sister.

23:34.543 --> 23:37.459
The one comfort I had

23:37.503 --> 23:40.767
was knowing that we would
be able to say our goodbyes.

23:40.810 --> 23:42.943
- But you never got to.
None of us did.

23:42.986 --> 23:45.772
- You asked why I am not angry.

23:45.815 --> 23:47.121
♪

23:47.164 --> 23:48.905
I was.

23:48.949 --> 23:52.692
For a very long time.

23:52.735 --> 23:55.782
I was the one in the car
the night she died.

23:55.825 --> 23:59.307
[shaky breathing]
I held her in my arms

23:59.350 --> 24:02.832
when she took her last breath,

24:02.876 --> 24:04.834
when she closed her eyes
for the last time,

24:04.878 --> 24:08.316
so you're damn right
I was angry,

24:08.359 --> 24:11.362
until one morning I woke up
and realized, "I want

24:11.406 --> 24:13.364
"to remember my wife with love,

24:13.408 --> 24:15.889
with a--with a smile,"

24:15.932 --> 24:17.760
and I couldn't do that
if I was carrying around

24:17.804 --> 24:20.284
all that anger.
I had to let it go,

24:20.328 --> 24:23.331
and the only way to do that

24:23.374 --> 24:24.680
was to forgive Charles Cole.

24:24.724 --> 24:27.030
- No, Dad, you forgave him

24:27.074 --> 24:28.989
because your faith told you to.

24:29.032 --> 24:31.165
- No, I forgave him

24:31.208 --> 24:34.037
because that's what your mother

24:34.081 --> 24:36.823
would have done.

24:36.866 --> 24:38.651
I forgave him because that's

24:38.694 --> 24:41.567
what I needed to do.

24:41.610 --> 24:44.047
♪

24:44.091 --> 24:46.093
[sighs]
Look...

24:46.136 --> 24:49.139
♪

24:49.183 --> 24:51.533
Your sister said that
the God Account

24:51.577 --> 24:52.708
sent you his name.

24:52.752 --> 24:54.754
I think that's for a reason.

24:54.797 --> 24:57.496
It's time for you...

24:57.539 --> 24:59.585
to let go, son,

24:59.628 --> 25:01.978
because if you don't...

25:02.022 --> 25:05.199
you will never be able
to move forward.

25:05.242 --> 25:10.683
♪

25:17.951 --> 25:20.910
[Emmit Fenn's
"Lost in Space" playing]

25:20.954 --> 25:27.961
♪

25:36.056 --> 25:39.363
- ♪ I wash away

25:39.407 --> 25:42.932
♪ In your river of gold

25:42.976 --> 25:45.152
♪

25:45.195 --> 25:48.590
♪ I'm losing this

25:48.634 --> 25:52.507
♪ On these dead-end roads

25:52.551 --> 25:59.558
♪

26:05.476 --> 26:06.869
- What are you doing here?

26:06.913 --> 26:09.219
- Um...
[stammering]

26:09.263 --> 26:11.613
I was hoping to speak
with you and Charles.

26:11.657 --> 26:14.094
- Charles isn't here.

26:14.137 --> 26:16.662
- Do you mind if I come in?

26:20.622 --> 26:23.494
- The engagement's off.

26:23.538 --> 26:26.106
- I'm sorry.

26:26.149 --> 26:27.977
I know how difficult
it must have been to find out

26:28.021 --> 26:30.153
something like that.

26:31.415 --> 26:33.809
But it was 17 years ago.

26:33.853 --> 26:36.725
Are you sure you just want
to end things?

26:37.900 --> 26:40.424
- I'm not the one
who ended it.

26:42.688 --> 26:45.995
After you
and your friend Miles left...

26:46.039 --> 26:49.042
I told Charles
that I was hurt...

26:49.085 --> 26:51.871
that he'd kept something
like that from me,

26:51.914 --> 26:55.396
but that at the end of the day,
I wanted to work through it.

26:55.439 --> 26:57.920
- What did he say?

26:57.964 --> 27:00.314
- That he still loved me,

27:00.357 --> 27:02.403
but we shouldn't get married.

27:02.446 --> 27:04.927
[melancholy music]

27:04.971 --> 27:07.626
- Why?

27:07.669 --> 27:09.366
- He said...

27:09.410 --> 27:11.847
I would see him differently

27:11.891 --> 27:13.936
knowing what he'd done,

27:13.980 --> 27:15.459
and I told him
that wasn't true,

27:15.503 --> 27:17.461
but he didn't believe me.

27:17.505 --> 27:18.985
♪

27:19.028 --> 27:22.292
He packed a bag and left.

27:22.336 --> 27:24.773
[sniffles]

27:24.817 --> 27:28.647
♪

27:31.867 --> 27:33.652
- Hey.

27:33.695 --> 27:35.436
- How did you find me?

27:35.479 --> 27:38.221
- Uh, actually,
Rakesh tracked your location

27:38.265 --> 27:39.614
using Find Friends.

27:39.658 --> 27:41.442
- What are you doing
down here?

27:41.485 --> 27:43.749
- Um...

27:43.792 --> 27:46.447
Charles broke off
his engagement to Angela.

27:46.490 --> 27:48.667
He said that she would
see him differently

27:48.710 --> 27:51.191
from now on
knowing about his past.

27:51.234 --> 27:54.150
- You think he's right?

27:54.194 --> 27:56.500
- I don't know.

27:59.939 --> 28:01.767
- My father thinks
I'm still holding on

28:01.810 --> 28:05.031
to my anger over losing my mom,

28:05.074 --> 28:07.294
that...

28:07.337 --> 28:09.470
if I don't let go,

28:09.513 --> 28:11.864
I'll never be able to move on.

28:11.907 --> 28:15.128
I'll never be able
to remember her...

28:15.171 --> 28:17.652
without feeling this way.

28:17.696 --> 28:19.393
- What do you think?

28:19.436 --> 28:22.091
- That even if he's right...

28:24.746 --> 28:27.706
I don't know how to let it go,

28:27.749 --> 28:30.143
or if I can.

28:32.928 --> 28:35.322
- You know what
scared me the most

28:35.365 --> 28:38.107
about reconnecting
with my mom?

28:39.674 --> 28:41.284
It was knowing that
if I forgave her,

28:41.328 --> 28:43.199
I would have to let go

28:43.243 --> 28:45.724
of all of that anger
that I carried around with me.

28:47.943 --> 28:50.293
And if I did...

28:51.381 --> 28:54.558
I might not know
who I was anymore.

28:54.602 --> 28:58.258
Wouldn't know
what to replace it with.

28:58.301 --> 29:01.652
And for a long time...

29:01.696 --> 29:04.307
that scared me more
than holding onto it.

29:06.048 --> 29:08.747
- How'd you get through it?

29:08.790 --> 29:11.010
[hopeful music]

29:11.053 --> 29:13.273
- You.

29:13.316 --> 29:16.015
Miles, you helped me
through it.

29:16.058 --> 29:17.799
♪

29:17.843 --> 29:20.628
Everything we've been doing
with the God Account...

29:20.671 --> 29:22.630
♪

29:22.673 --> 29:25.024
That replaced all of it.

29:25.067 --> 29:27.113
♪

29:27.156 --> 29:30.333
- Well, thank you for always
being honest with me.

29:30.377 --> 29:32.988
♪

29:33.032 --> 29:35.295
- Uh...

29:35.338 --> 29:36.383
about that.

29:36.426 --> 29:38.951
Um...

29:38.994 --> 29:41.127
I got that promotion.

29:41.170 --> 29:42.345
- You did?

29:42.389 --> 29:44.695
Well, hey, why didn't you
tell me?

29:44.739 --> 29:46.610
- Well, uh...

29:46.654 --> 29:49.483
'cause it would take me away
from these stories

29:49.526 --> 29:52.268
and all the people
we've been helping.

29:52.312 --> 29:55.054
♪

29:55.097 --> 29:57.186
- So...

29:57.230 --> 30:00.363
you think you've got
one more story in you?

30:00.407 --> 30:03.149
- Are you saying you want
to help Charles Cole?

30:03.192 --> 30:06.456
- I think it's time
that I stopped running away

30:06.500 --> 30:08.502
from the past.

30:08.545 --> 30:10.286
But...

30:10.330 --> 30:12.854
I can't do that without you.

30:12.898 --> 30:14.943
- Well, you don't have to.

30:14.987 --> 30:17.554
♪

30:17.598 --> 30:20.993
- Did Angela have an idea
of where Charles might be?

30:21.036 --> 30:23.038
- No.
[sighs]

30:23.082 --> 30:25.867
Too bad there's no
"Find Friend Suggestions" app.

30:25.911 --> 30:27.434
♪

30:27.477 --> 30:29.349
- Actually...

30:29.392 --> 30:32.004
we may have something better.

30:32.047 --> 30:34.049
♪

30:34.093 --> 30:35.834
- So what are we looking for?

30:35.877 --> 30:37.966
- Some place from Charles' past
that might be important.

30:38.010 --> 30:40.577
Somewhere along the Spiral
he might be at.

30:40.621 --> 30:42.971
- What about Crowley's Bar?

30:43.015 --> 30:44.930
It's where Charles went
that night after he graduated

30:44.973 --> 30:45.931
from the Academy.

30:45.974 --> 30:47.410
- Okay.

30:47.454 --> 30:49.586
"Crowley's Bar."

30:49.630 --> 30:51.371
Address is...

30:51.414 --> 30:52.763
[computer beeps]

30:52.807 --> 30:55.941
[laughs]
Guys, this bar is practically

30:55.984 --> 30:58.508
in the center of the Spiral.

30:58.552 --> 31:00.815
- You mind if I go alone?

31:00.859 --> 31:06.473
♪

31:06.516 --> 31:08.692
[phone vibrating]

31:08.736 --> 31:11.913
♪

31:11.957 --> 31:14.307
[car honking]

31:14.350 --> 31:16.526
[flames crackling]

31:16.570 --> 31:19.486
[indistinct chatter]

31:19.529 --> 31:21.227
Hey, is--is everyone okay?

31:21.270 --> 31:23.794
- I don't know.
Fire department's on its way.

31:23.838 --> 31:26.797
[tense music]

31:26.841 --> 31:31.977
♪

31:32.020 --> 31:33.369
- Charles!

31:33.413 --> 31:34.805
Hey, hey, what are you
doing here?

31:34.849 --> 31:36.155
- I was down the street
when I saw the fire.

31:36.198 --> 31:37.721
There's two people
trapped inside.

31:37.765 --> 31:40.072
We don't have time to wait.
- Okay, let's go.

31:40.115 --> 31:42.030
♪

31:42.074 --> 31:43.771
[coughing]
- Stay close.

31:43.814 --> 31:45.816
- Mm-hmm.
[both coughing, panting]

31:45.860 --> 31:48.254
[fire alarm beeping
sporadically]

31:48.297 --> 31:49.603
- Hello, is anyone there?

31:49.646 --> 31:52.127
- Somebody help, please!

31:52.171 --> 31:53.912
Somebody help!

31:53.955 --> 31:56.001
[both panting, coughing]

31:56.044 --> 31:57.654
Please wake up, Mom!
- Stand back.

31:57.698 --> 31:59.482
- Mom, wake up!
- [grunts]

31:59.526 --> 32:01.441
[dramatic music]

32:01.484 --> 32:03.225
- I've got her, go!

32:03.269 --> 32:05.358
- Okay.
Hey.

32:05.401 --> 32:07.751
Okay, I got you.
It's gonna be okay.

32:07.795 --> 32:09.492
[coughs]
It's gonna be okay.

32:09.536 --> 32:11.190
- [grunts]

32:11.233 --> 32:14.193
- Oh, my God!
- Guys--

32:14.236 --> 32:19.024
♪

32:19.067 --> 32:21.548
- [coughing]
- You okay?

32:21.591 --> 32:28.598
♪

32:31.558 --> 32:34.474
[music quiets]

32:34.517 --> 32:35.475
Help.

32:35.518 --> 32:37.259
[fire truck honking]

32:37.303 --> 32:39.696
- [grunts]
Just put her down here.

32:39.740 --> 32:42.351
[sirens wailing]

32:42.395 --> 32:43.831
Miss?

32:43.874 --> 32:45.702
Miss, can you hear me?

32:45.746 --> 32:48.662
- Okay, buddy.

32:48.705 --> 32:51.665
[dramatic music]

32:51.708 --> 32:55.060
- Come on.

32:55.103 --> 32:56.931
- [coughs, gasps]

32:56.975 --> 32:58.541
[coughing]

32:58.585 --> 33:01.283
- It's okay.
- [gasping, coughing]

33:01.327 --> 33:06.375
♪

33:12.512 --> 33:16.559
[mellow music]

33:16.603 --> 33:18.866
- Everyone okay?
- Yeah.

33:18.909 --> 33:22.217
Apparently one of the tenants
left their stove on.

33:22.261 --> 33:24.437
Luckily the fire was contained.
- Yeah.

33:24.480 --> 33:26.917
Can you just give us a minute?

33:31.270 --> 33:33.576
What are you doing
down here, Miles?

33:33.620 --> 33:36.362
- I was on my way
to Crowley's Bar,

33:36.405 --> 33:39.539
hoping to find you.

33:39.582 --> 33:41.758
- I haven't been back
to that place since the night

33:41.802 --> 33:43.456
of the accident,

33:43.499 --> 33:46.067
and I haven't had a drink
since that night,

33:46.111 --> 33:48.548
but...
[sighs]

33:48.591 --> 33:50.506
I don't know,
today of all days,

33:50.550 --> 33:52.073
I somehow just found myself

33:52.117 --> 33:54.380
standing outside of it,

33:54.423 --> 33:56.556
and before I could head in,
I saw the fire and I knew

33:56.599 --> 33:58.297
I had to do something,

33:58.340 --> 34:01.082
no matter what
the consequences.

34:04.999 --> 34:07.132
- I know about Angela.

34:07.175 --> 34:08.872
You broke things off with her.

34:08.916 --> 34:10.744
I...

34:10.787 --> 34:12.093
I'm sorry.

34:12.137 --> 34:14.052
- Not your fault.

34:14.095 --> 34:15.575
It was gonna happen eventually.

34:15.618 --> 34:17.838
- What do you mean?

34:17.881 --> 34:20.362
- Well, after I got out
of prison...

34:20.406 --> 34:23.887
most of my friends didn't want
to have anything to do with me.

34:23.931 --> 34:26.064
I didn't blame them,

34:26.107 --> 34:28.979
and over the years
I've only had a handful

34:29.023 --> 34:31.373
of serious relationships...

34:31.417 --> 34:34.246
and each time, I would
tell them what happened.

34:34.289 --> 34:36.422
You know, what I did,
because I never wanted

34:36.465 --> 34:38.772
to hide it,

34:38.815 --> 34:41.122
but inevitably...
[sighs]

34:41.166 --> 34:42.819
we would grow apart.

34:42.863 --> 34:44.952
Things would end.

34:44.995 --> 34:48.086
- That's why you didn't
tell Angela.

34:48.129 --> 34:50.218
- I wanted to.

34:50.262 --> 34:52.002
[melancholy music]

34:52.046 --> 34:55.093
Kept on telling myself
that I would and I never did.

34:55.136 --> 34:56.790
♪

34:56.833 --> 35:00.054
I guess I just didn't want her
to look at me

35:00.098 --> 35:02.796
the same way everyone else does
when they find out.

35:02.839 --> 35:06.974
♪

35:07.017 --> 35:08.932
- [sighs]

35:08.976 --> 35:11.109
Maybe she won't.

35:11.152 --> 35:14.112
Maybe those relationships

35:14.155 --> 35:16.723
didn't end because
they pushed you away

35:16.766 --> 35:20.074
after they found out.

35:20.118 --> 35:23.033
Maybe they ended
because you pushed them away.

35:23.077 --> 35:30.084
♪

35:32.086 --> 35:34.523
No matter what happens
with the Academy--

35:34.567 --> 35:37.047
whether you get in
or you don't--

35:37.091 --> 35:40.094
your life moving forward
belongs with Angela.

35:40.138 --> 35:42.662
♪

35:42.705 --> 35:45.012
You need to let go
of the past--

35:45.055 --> 35:47.580
of the life you lost--
and start living

35:47.623 --> 35:49.582
the life you have.

35:49.625 --> 35:51.453
[inspirational music]

35:51.497 --> 35:53.542
It's time both of us do.

35:53.586 --> 35:55.631
♪

35:55.675 --> 35:58.634
[Dashboard Confessional's
"Heart Beat Here" playing]

35:58.678 --> 36:00.245
♪

36:00.288 --> 36:02.464
- ♪ Come on home
and let yourself heal ♪

36:02.508 --> 36:05.293
- When I was eight years old,
my mother died

36:05.337 --> 36:07.991
in a car accident...

36:08.035 --> 36:11.125
and until recently,
I assumed

36:11.169 --> 36:14.215
that was the defining moment
in my life.

36:14.259 --> 36:16.174
- ♪ Let your heart

36:16.217 --> 36:18.785
- I didn't realize
the real moment would come

36:18.828 --> 36:21.440
17 years later.

36:21.483 --> 36:24.007
We usually think
of second chances

36:24.051 --> 36:26.227
as a way to move on,

36:26.271 --> 36:28.534
move forward.

36:28.577 --> 36:30.623
♪

36:30.666 --> 36:33.016
- ♪ Chasing
what you feel inside ♪

36:33.060 --> 36:35.628
- I'm sorry.

36:35.671 --> 36:38.413
- ♪ I will take
your path as mine ♪

36:38.457 --> 36:41.808
- But I think second chances

36:41.851 --> 36:44.985
are about acceptance.

36:45.028 --> 36:47.292
That's why they're so rare.

36:47.335 --> 36:50.425
- ♪ The pulse just grows

36:50.469 --> 36:51.948
♪

36:51.992 --> 36:53.994
- Because accepting
who you are

36:54.037 --> 36:56.039
and what you really want

36:56.083 --> 36:59.826
isn't as easy
as we like to think.

36:59.869 --> 37:01.958
- I just read your piece
about the firefighter.

37:02.002 --> 37:03.221
It was excellent,

37:03.264 --> 37:05.484
a nice way to end that series.

37:05.527 --> 37:06.702
- Thanks.

37:06.746 --> 37:09.662
- Good luck in features.

37:09.705 --> 37:12.621
- [laughs softly]

37:12.665 --> 37:15.015
- But more often than not,

37:15.058 --> 37:16.669
it brings us to the place

37:16.712 --> 37:20.020
we should have been coming to
all along.

37:20.063 --> 37:24.242
- ♪ I wear my ring
to know what's at stake ♪

37:24.285 --> 37:26.244
- I'm glad you're here.

37:26.287 --> 37:28.202
- Me, too.

37:28.246 --> 37:31.161
♪

37:31.205 --> 37:33.903
I helped Charles Cole.

37:33.947 --> 37:36.428
- Mind me asking...

37:36.471 --> 37:39.692
what changed your mind?

37:39.735 --> 37:41.563
- You did.

37:41.607 --> 37:44.305
- ♪ The pulse just grows

37:44.349 --> 37:47.265
- I want to remember her
the same way you do.

37:47.308 --> 37:50.311
I want to remember
how lucky I was

37:50.355 --> 37:52.182
that she was my mom...

37:52.226 --> 37:54.359
- ♪ Let your heart beat here

37:54.402 --> 37:57.492
- Even if only
for a short time.

37:57.536 --> 37:58.972
- ♪ So loud

37:59.015 --> 38:01.409
- I know that's what
she would have wanted.

38:01.453 --> 38:03.324
- ♪ So clear

38:03.368 --> 38:05.892
- Dad, can I ask you something?
- Hmm?

38:05.935 --> 38:08.590
- ♪ Beat here

38:08.634 --> 38:10.462
- What would you have said
to her if you had

38:10.505 --> 38:12.594
gotten the chance?

38:12.638 --> 38:15.205
♪

38:15.249 --> 38:17.077
- Thank you...

38:17.120 --> 38:18.905
for loving me.

38:18.948 --> 38:20.950
- ♪ I feel it in my ribs

38:20.994 --> 38:24.606
♪ Feel it in my soul

38:24.650 --> 38:29.132
♪ The pulse just grows

38:29.176 --> 38:30.612
♪

38:30.656 --> 38:32.440
♪ So loud and so clear

38:32.484 --> 38:35.443
[both laughing]

38:35.487 --> 38:37.880
- [sniffles]

38:37.924 --> 38:41.362
- ♪ Let your heart beat here

38:41.406 --> 38:43.930
- I knew I should have waited
to put on my mascara.

38:43.973 --> 38:46.933
- Oh.
[all laughing]

38:46.976 --> 38:48.761
Mm.

38:48.804 --> 38:52.678
- ♪ So loud and so clear

38:52.721 --> 38:55.333
♪ Let your heart

38:55.376 --> 38:58.423
♪ Beat here

38:58.466 --> 39:00.990
♪ Yeah, let your heart

39:01.034 --> 39:04.646
♪ Beat here

39:04.690 --> 39:06.866
♪ Let your heart

39:06.909 --> 39:10.086
♪ Beat here

39:10.130 --> 39:12.654
- I visited my mom

39:12.698 --> 39:14.308
with my dad and Ali yesterday.

39:14.352 --> 39:16.832
- How was it?

39:16.876 --> 39:20.227
- It was actually nice.

39:22.360 --> 39:24.449
- It's good you went.
- Mm-hmm.

39:24.492 --> 39:27.887
It was exactly where I needed
to be.

39:29.105 --> 39:32.152
Too bad you're no longer
writing about the God Account.

39:32.195 --> 39:34.894
It won't be long
until we find Falken.

39:34.937 --> 39:37.853
- Yeah, um, about that.

39:37.897 --> 39:40.856
I sort of turned down the job.

39:40.900 --> 39:42.597
- What? Why?

39:42.641 --> 39:44.425
- [sighs]
In these last few months,

39:44.469 --> 39:47.254
I've finally figured out
who I want to be

39:47.297 --> 39:50.344
and how I'm gonna get there...

39:50.388 --> 39:53.391
and I'm not willing
to trade that for anything.

39:54.479 --> 39:57.046
- I'm glad,
'cause doing this without you

39:57.090 --> 39:58.483
would not be the same,

39:58.526 --> 40:01.007
but I am still buying you
the drink

40:01.050 --> 40:02.400
for getting the promotion,

40:02.443 --> 40:04.924
even if you turned it down.

40:06.404 --> 40:09.407
Unless you have plans with Eli.

40:11.844 --> 40:14.020
- Yeah, about that, too.

40:14.063 --> 40:15.891
[mellow music]

40:15.935 --> 40:18.633
We kind of broke up.

40:18.677 --> 40:20.853
- What happened?

40:20.896 --> 40:22.768
♪

40:22.811 --> 40:25.031
- He wasn't the one.

40:25.074 --> 40:29.035
♪

40:29.078 --> 40:30.471
[knocking on door]

40:30.515 --> 40:31.994
- Miles!

40:32.038 --> 40:33.431
Miles!

40:33.474 --> 40:35.824
both: Rakesh.

40:35.868 --> 40:38.827
[knocking continues]

40:38.871 --> 40:40.786
♪

40:40.829 --> 40:43.484
- Bro, is everything okay?
- Uh, it's better than okay.

40:43.528 --> 40:46.792
Um, I found Falken.

40:46.835 --> 40:48.837
- Wait, you did?
How?

40:48.881 --> 40:52.188
- So the address of the fire
was 55 144th Street,

40:52.232 --> 40:53.929
and the next number
in the Fibonacci Sequence

40:53.973 --> 40:55.235
is 89.

40:55.278 --> 40:57.455
So I looked up 89 144th Street,

40:57.498 --> 40:58.760
and guess who owns the place?

40:58.804 --> 41:01.720
- Who?
- Bill and Lila Chase,

41:01.763 --> 41:03.069
Henry's parents.

41:03.112 --> 41:05.419
It was his childhood home.

41:05.463 --> 41:08.422
[curious music]

41:08.466 --> 41:15.473
♪

41:26.527 --> 41:29.269
Should we knock, or...?

41:29.312 --> 41:31.793
♪

41:31.837 --> 41:34.056
[knocking on door]

41:34.100 --> 41:39.192
♪

41:39.235 --> 41:41.542
- It's unlocked.

41:41.586 --> 41:48.549
♪

42:01.867 --> 42:04.696
- It looks like no one's
lived here in years.

42:04.739 --> 42:07.307
♪

42:07.350 --> 42:10.310
[approaching footsteps]

42:10.353 --> 42:11.964
♪

42:12.007 --> 42:14.096
- Hello, Miles.

42:14.140 --> 42:15.533
♪

42:15.576 --> 42:18.318
- Pria?
- Wait, you lied to us?

42:18.361 --> 42:21.277
- Had to know
I could trust you.

42:21.321 --> 42:23.758
- Are you Falken?

42:23.802 --> 42:26.282
- It's time you knew the truth.

42:26.326 --> 42:30.373
♪

42:44.431 --> 42:47.390
[curious music]

42:47.434 --> 42:54.441
♪

43:03.319 --> 43:04.538
- Greg, move your head.

43:04.582 --> 43:05.800
- I have an idea!
